traces the development of ideas of the protestant interest, explaining how such ideas were used to combat the perceived threats to the European states system posed by universal monarchy, and showing how the necessity of defending protestantism within Europe became a theme in British and Hanoverian foreign policy. Drawing on a wide range of printed and manuscript material in both Britain and Germany, the book emphasises the importance of a European context for eighteenth-century British history, and contributes to debates about the justification of monarchy and the nature of identity in Britain. Dr ANDREW C. THOMPSON is Lecturer in History, Queens' College, Cambridge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aProtestantismzGermanyxHistoryy17th century. 0aProtestantismzGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 0aProtestantismzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aProtestantismzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aReligion and politicszGermanyxHistoryy17th century. 0aReligion and politicszGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 0aReligion and politicszGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aReligion and politicszGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMilitary History. 4aModern History. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aEuropean states system.  aearly eighteenth century.  apolitics.  aprotestant faith.  areligion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615451540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846154515423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846154515/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles